docs.text: let me start off by saying that leading up to the release of the latest bond film , i really wasn't looking forward to it as much as i have with some of the previous films .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i'm not sure if it was the fairly lackluster trailers or the ever-present dread that the next film will fall back into the miserable ways of the timothy dalton years .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i'm happy to report that any doubts were erased after about the first 10 minutes of the film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: by that point , it was evident that mr . bond was back with a vengeance .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: all doubts would have probably been erased sooner except for the fact that the first ten minutes of the film weren't exactly a pleasant experience .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it seems that nobody told the geniuses working at the theater that the house lights are supposed to be turned off when the movie starts .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it took a reminder from an audience member to clue them in .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i guess they can be excused though , taking tickets and cleaning up popcorn between shows is extremely taxing on the brain .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: anyway , after somebody remembered what the light switch was for , i settled in for bond .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i think the most noticeable aspect of this , the 19th film in the series , is that it really goes back to the almost tongue in cheek style of the roger moore films .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there were probably more one-liners in this movie than in the last several combined .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: and bond's last one-liner in the film is about the best of the series .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the world is not enough also contained perhaps the most action of any movie of the series .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: everything from wild boat chases to the usual assortment of cool bond gadgets trotted out just when there seems to be no way out for 007 .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: for the most part , the action sequences worked very well .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: although , there were a couple of times that i thought some things were a bit over the top , even for a bond film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i think some of the blame can be laid at the feet of director michael apted .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: while he did a good job for the most part , there were points in the movie , specifically during action sequences , that he seemed to loose site of the fact that he was making essentially an action film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: most noticeably sequences on a snow covered mountain and one involving bond getting through a closing door looked like apted thought he was filming some sort of high brow art movie .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he almost seemed like he didn't know what he was doing .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but they were brief scenes and really shouldn't take away from the otherwise solid job that apted did in directing .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: if you have ever seen a bond film , you won't be shocked to learn that plot has never been their strong suit .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the world is not enough is no exception .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this time we have yet another over villain that bond has to stop for the good of the world .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: 007 matches wits with the terrorist renard ( robert carlyle ) , a man who has a bullet lodged in his brain that makes him impervious to pain .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: why this point is included is beyond me .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: they took great pains to explain his condition , but it only came up later in the movie as a scene that can only be described as looking like an afterthought .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: anyway , renard , like the typical terrorist that he is , is bent on some harebrained scheme involving a mid-east oil pipeline .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i guess world domination just isn't as attractive to terrorists as a money making venture anymore .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: bond is brought in to protect the pipeline's owner , elektra king ( sophie marceau ) , who is the daughter of one of renard's recent victims .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: along the way , bond has to enlist the help of a nuclear scientist , dr . christmas jones ( denise richards ) , and his old rival valentin zukovsky ( robert carlyle ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: like all bond films , you basically just have to suspend disbelief over the plot , since it is ridiculous beyond words .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: my biggest complaint would be that it was about the most disjointed of any of the bond films .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there was at least one point that i had to stop and try to remember why bond was where he was and why he was doing what he was doing .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the buddy that i saw the movie with was completely confused over an earlier kidnapping of marceau's character .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it was alluded to earlier in the movie briefly -- although not included in the film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: later , it became a big part of the story and left him with the distinct feeling that he had missed something .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but because it is a bond film , the beautiful women and nifty gadgets seem to make you forget about script problems quite quickly .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: after all , it isn't shakespeare .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: how about the cast ?
docs.label: positive

docs.text: brosnan seems to get better with each of his appearances as 007 .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i grew up with the roger moore version of bond , so i really enjoyed the lighter style that brosnan brings to the character .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: judi dench , as m , had a bigger role in this film than in her two previous appearances in the role .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: she brought the talent with her that one would expect from an oscar winner .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: robbie coltrane was easily one of the best parts in goldeneye , so it was nice to see his russian mobster character revived in this movie .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: coltrane gets more screen time , which simply leads to him stealing even more scenes .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: then there are the bond girls .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: sophie marceau might be one of the most beautiful actresses working today .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there is just something about her breathtaking eyes that makes her a natural to play the innocent victim .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: those that saw her in braveheart know she is more than just a pretty face .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: marceau may be the most talented actress to ever play a bond love interest .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: then we have denise richards .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there was no doubt in my mind that she was cast exclusively for her looks .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: and after you see the outfits she wears , you won't have any trouble guessing what part of her anatomy caught the producer's eyes .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i was pleasantly surprised to find that she really did a good job playing a nuclear scientist .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: admittedly , there was one point that the audience snickered a bit at one of her technical lines of dialogue , but other than that she stacks up ( no pun intended ) to her bond girl predecessors nicely .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i must say that the biggest disappointment was robert carlyle's character .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: while carlyle did a fine job with the material that he had , his character just never worked for me .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the producers tried very hard to add more complexity to his character , but it just never quite got off the ground .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i guess i was hoping for a bit more regarding the whole impervious to pain aspect of his character , but the writers decided to play up the emotional side of his character .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this might have worked well in another movie , but i don't go to see bond movies for their deep characterizations .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: last , but not least , we have desmond llewelyn as q . this is the 17th appearance for llewelyn as bond's gadget guy , and he is as good as ever .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: although his screen time has grown far more limited in the past few films , he is still a treat to watch .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: rumors abound that this may be his last appearance in the role .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he says future appearances are up to a higher power .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the producers have introduced his protege and future replacement , a bumbling and somewhat pompous character played by comedy master john cleese .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: while we don't see much of him in this film , i think it is fair to say that desmond llewelyn's legacy , whenever it is passed on , will be in very capable hands .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: so how does it stack up ?
docs.label: positive

docs.text: despite some problems , the world is not enough is a very entertaining movie .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: and , all things considered , what problems it does have are small compared to some that have plagued earlier bond movies .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this is easily the best of the brosnan films .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it may even be the best of the entire series , certainly in the top 3 .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: one thing is for sure , even after 19 movies , there is still plenty of life left in the james bond series .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: here's looking forward to bond number 20 .
docs.label: positive
